column168: Original comments:  No damage. This package was shipped without any of the proper certifications/markings/paperwork. The package was discovered because it was poorly packed, so the tank ripped out of the box it was in.  New Comments: Hello Tammy, there was some confusion with this one from an Admin. This package came in as an undeclared HAZMAT, no labeling and no HAZMAT service code, but it was noticed by the type of product, a tank of refrigerant. The Admin held it and didn't reach out to management or safety right away, but did reach out to the shipper about it and they stated that someone would pick it up. The Admin then thought since someone was going to pick it up that it didn't need any type of SCM Sentry. Then we got a call back saying they would not retrieve it. I did speak with this admin about the importance of when in doubt to contact management, district safety, or PGH safety with any questions regarding HAZMAT?s or even something resembling a HAZAMT and gave him the Internal FedEx Hazmat Operation Hotline and where he can find it on the Safety page . I also explained that it would need to go through the HAP process and coded as a 97 and a new label would need created through there putting on a new service code for a HAZMAT. I am currently doing the BCSA test for Damaged Hazardous Material Reporting today and will conduct a full out audit for the current year. I have it planned for Safety week, and the new fiscal year, to conduct a special emphasis meeting with all Admin over the importance of safe and timely HAZMAT dispositions and handling.

column168: Driver arrived at the Boise Price to get loaded with crude oil from lease.  The road to the location not in good condition due to a work-over rig having done work recently.  As the driver was leaving the location, he stated that he heard something pop. He immediately stopped and pulled the hood to inspect the shocks, but then saw oil on the ground and a mud flap sticking in the barrel of the tanker.  The driver did not have phone service so he sent a message to my Terminal Manager via the onboard communication system.  He then went and vented the trailer to stop the leak from spraying as bad as it was.  The pumper drove up to the scene and assisted in notification to the terminal.  Driver tied a rag around the wires adjacent to the hole and pushed into the opening cutting down the release.  The leaking trailer continued for approximately an hour until it was off-loaded by second tanker we sent to the scene to assist.  Driver bermed the area immediately surrounding the leak, but crude exceeded the bermed area and entered the adjacent pond.
column169: The investigation found that the tractor mud flap bracket could be drilled and have a pin installed preventing the flap from working itself up.  All units will have this pin installed or mud flaps changed out so that this does not recur.

column168: On June 7, 2017 at 1603 hours, an FRA Inspector discovered NATX 280033, a loaded UN 1307, Xylene tank car to have wetness from the liquid line flange. column168: On June 13, 2017, XPO Logistics (XEN Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN2794, Batteries Wet, Filled With Acid, 8, (PRO#437620083) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel notified a leak coming from the trailer (3130092) from the XTM Terminal out in the yard. The caller indicated that the trailer has batteries in the trailer and it is unknown in the amount released or the cause at this time. 2110 ERTS dispatched Wenck Associates out of Woodbury, MN. Contractor indicated that there are 8 large batteries that have all shifted and appear to be leaking. Contractor indicated that approximately 5 gallons of product has been released to a 10' x 15' area of asphalt and approximately 5 gallons of product inside the trailer. Contractor is using soda ash to neutralize the release. Contractor has finished cleaning the outside area and is moving to clean the inside at this time.Contractor is wrapping two damaged batteries in poly and placing them on a pallet. Contractor indicated that each battery weighs approximately 375 pounds. Contractor indicated that there is a total of 16 batteries damaged. Contractor has placed 2 batteries wrapped in poly on a pallet and is working on banding them together to make sure there is no further release. Contractor indicated that there are various parts and pieces on the batteries that appear to be damaged.  Contractor has finished cleanup activities. Contractor generated (2) 55-gallon poly drums of cleanup debris and PPE. Contractor has wrapped the batteries and poly and staged them back in the trailer per Chee Vang with XPO. Contractor has staged the two waste drums in OS & D.

column168: Tank Car GATX 70656 was discovered venting to atmosphere at 0630AM. This tank car was received by the railyard about two weeks prior to the incident, and was constructively placed on a yard track until the patron could receive the car at their facility. Our Emergency Response Plan was initiated and began with notifications to the following agencies and entities; Local EMS, Local Fire Department, NRC, FRA, PUC, PEMA, PA DEP, Norfolk Southern Hazmat Compliance Officer and Northridge Group Inc. Environmental Response. The action plan was to continue to let the car vent and polymerize until the material became stable to begin the clean up process. After a mechanical inspection of the car, it was discovered that the liquid line gasket had a three inch rupture on it causing the car to vent through the rupture. The cause of the reaction is currently unknown, however it is suspected that there may have been some contamination in the tank car prior to loading. The shipper of the material flew their chemists to the site to examine and test the material, temperature of the car and temperature of the contents of the car. The command center was located at the Lock Yard Office for mitigating the incident. The release duration occurred for 20 hours and clean up occurred for 8 hours. Through this duration, the car was attended by our emergency response contractor, Northridge, to ensure control of the site.
column169: No recommendations as this was the shipper's issue. Currently our patron will not be accepting this material from the shipper. Tests thus far have not provided a definitive answer of why the material reacted. The car was loaded, shipped and received at the Lock Haven Yard with no issues.

6/15/2017: At approximately 1845 hours, while performing a routine outbound train inspection, CR Car Inspector noticed a gas odor and heard pressure escaping from tank car UTLX 956289, containing the residue of Petroleum Gases, Liquefied (Propane).      Further inspections by both shipper representatives from Sun Refining and Marketing, and, Hepaco (CR Emergency Response contractor), revealed the "A" end liquid valve appeared to be closed and the closure plug for said valve was noted as tool tight.  The valve was further snugged closed and closure plug was also snugged tight, whereby stopping the release.  Noted by Hepaco that car contained approximately 160 psi internal pressure at time of inspection.    Car was authorized by CR's A. Richter to be cut out of the outbound train and moved back to the shipper.  Shipper will depressurize and flare remaining contents in car, and car will be forwarded to certified shop for inspection of liquid valve for repair/replacement.

column168: A shipment of lead acid batteries was loaded into 95 gallon salvage containers by the customer.  The driver picked them up and transported the shipment to the intermediate truck transfer facility.  While unloading the trailer's contents into another trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility, the top-heavy drums on small pallets became unstable and toppled onto the side.  The drums were uprighted, but one began leaking from the lid.  A response crew was summoned and repackaged the entire shipment properly into suitable containers.  The shipment was then loaded without further incident.
column169: The customer was notified of the incident.  The customer should not have packaged the batteries in this manner and the driver should not have picked them up in this condition.  The driver was disciplined for the incident.

column168: On June 6, 2017, at 17:27 hours, a passing train notified the crew on the Q38906, of a vapor cloud coming from a tank car at Railroad milepost QR 100.9 in Saugerties, NY. The crew noticed a vapor cloud from the top of RCRX 1522, a loaded tank car of UN1789, hydrochloric acid. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Reagent Chemical, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2017-06-06-00265. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene. Hepaco found the vapor line flange releasing vapor from a damaged flange gasket and less than tool tight flange bolts. The bolts were tightened and the release of vapors stopped. The shipper representative, Kevin Callais,(281) 404-9728 was notified of the situation found. The release was temporarily secured and RCRX 1522 was then moved to CSX Kingston, NY Yard for further inspection and repairs.     At the CSX Kingston, NY Yard RCRX 1522 was monitored using HCL acid tubes to ensure no vapors were being emitted out of the immediate tank car area. A replacement flange gasket was obtained and Specialized Professional Services Inc. (SPSI) a qualified C-6 repair shop was contracted to replace the flange gasket, properly secure and perform a pressure test to re-qualify tank car RCRX 1522. After the tank car was re-qualified it was released back into transportation.     NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60  Cause code:551

column168: On 6/16/17 at approximately 2115 hours an IMTT Chemical Operator was overseeing the loading of a rail car with Furfuryl Alcohol when he noticed that the loading pump was leaking from the pump seal.  The IMTT Chemical Operator immediately contacted his supervisor who assisted with blowing the pump clear, closing all the valves to the pump and securing the tank from which the product was being pumped from.  The IMTT Supervisor contacted US Ecology (IMTT's OSRO) to respond to the area and begin a cleanup operation.
column169: On 6/17/17 an IMTT Maintenance crew was able to remove the damaged seal and replace it with a new one and put the pump back into service.  The customer of the product was notified of the incident however due to the small amount of product lost (approx. 5 gal) there was no reimbursement to the customer.  Preventative maintenance is performed on pumps on an as needed basis.

column168: Driver arrived at store to unload gasoline into store UST around 2200 on 06/15/2017.  Driver connected product hose to trailer compartment and opened trailer valve without connecting hose to store UST.  Approximately 52 gallons of gasoline spilled onto pavement and into man-made retention system.  Lawrenceville FD was called and responded to contain spill.  Aqua Terra Recycling was dispatched to clean spill.  Aqua-Terra dispatched a small trailer emergency spill unit and a vacuum truck.  Aqua-Terra noticed that there was a strong odor of gasoline around the trench drains and the storm drain that goes underground along the front of the adjacent McDonald's.  Aqua Terra personnel was shown where the retention pond was for the two properties. It was observed that there was free product in the storm inlet in front of McDonald's.  Aqua-Terra moved their vacuum truck to this area and commenced to remove water and product.  Lawrenceville had received periods of heavy rain prior to our arrival.  This had moved most of the product into the storm drain and the down gradient retention pond.  Absorbent booms were placed at the inlet to the McDonald's storm drain and the out fall of the storm drain that falls into the retention pond.  Equipment and material used: 1 bundle of absorbent pads, 3 bags of absorbent material, 1 bundle of booms, 2 metal 55 gallon drums.  Disposal of 52 gallons of liquid, two drums of absorbent material and pads.
column169: Driver retrained on proper unloading procedures.  Current procedures dictate product hoses are connected to UST before they are connected to the trailer to prevent spills.

column168: The cargo tank motor vehicle arrived in good order to the delivery location.  The driver failed to make correct calculations in determining the empty volume remaining in the underground storage tank.  The driver made proper connections and began product flow.  The driver observed product flowing upward and out of the fill inlet.  Drover immediately stopped product flow and notified first responders.  An estimated 70-152 gallons of product flowed towards the street curb and flowed down the curb way approximately 500 feet.  A small amount of product flowed over a city sewer services manhole cover.  During clean up activities the manhole cover was opened and inspected.  A public works employee, Calvin Henson, stated that the sanitary sewer equipment was not affected by the spilled product.  A third party vendor was hired and performed clean up activities. The clean up team worked for approximately sixteen hours performing the clean up work.    Inspection of the underground storage tank overflow protection equipment (flapper) was defective.  The overflow protection equipment is designed to stop product flow when 90% capacity is reached.
column169: Driver will be disciplined and subjected to remedial training in calculating underground storage tank capacity.  The owner of the underground storage tank will perform necessary tank maintenance to repair the overflow protection system.

column168: On June 02, 2017 during unloading operations, terminal personnel discovered a (1) 2200-pound poly supersac containing UN1492 Potassium Persulphate that had an apparent forklift puncture. The caller stated that there is only about 300-pounds left in the supersac thus approximately 1700-pounds release. A contractor was dispatched who contained and cleaned the release and overpacked the damaged supersac. The salvaged and waste material was staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

According to the caller, the driver of trailer (4860-0252) He went to do a walk around his trailer and noticed a leak coming from his trailer. An environmental contractor was dispatched and advised that the trailer is loaded with 120-gallon agricultural tanks. Approximately 20 gallons released from the lid at the very last tank. The contractor advised that the pump assembly on top of the tote had an open valve which allowed for the release. The valve will be closed and (chemtape) will be placed over the valve to ensure it does not open again. The tank lid appears to be tight and intact. Approximately 20 gallons released to a 3' x 40' area of the grooved trailer floor with minimal drips to the loose soil below. The contractor hand excavated the soil and will decon the trailer floor. The wastes were collected for disposal/

column168: On June 21, 2017, XPO Logistics (XCW Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1070, Nitrous Oxide, 2.2, (5.1), (PRO#462549710) release. The cylinder is hissing, and the contractor stated that it is due to a faulty release valve. The valve cannot be tighten, so the contractor will monitor the cylinder until the hissing stops. The cylinder will be shipped onto the consignee and the contractor is departing site with no waste being generated.

column168: CTMV was making a left turn from SH288 frontage road to FM2004 at intersection controlled by red/yellow/green traffic light.  When the light turned green, driver accelerated too fast for the 90 degree left turn.  Excessive momentum caused the CTMV to rollover onto right/passenger side.  The CTMV slid on pavement and came to rest partially on pavement and right shoulder.  The impact on the right side of the semi-trailer caused an internal bulkhead to crack.  Approximately 250 gallons of product leaked through the crack into the void between compartments.  The product leaked out of the bottom drain opening that provides drainage for the void space between the compartments.  The product leaked onto the pavement and shoulder.  A third party vendor provided clean up activity by picking up the product and replacing the contaminated soil.  First responder authorities closed the intersection for approximately twelve hours during the clean up to prevent public access to the area.

column168: A Clean Harbors driver pickup a Clean Harbors trailer at the Clean Harbors Spring Grove Facility in Spring Grove, OH. column168: On Friday June 9, 2017 at 6:41 AM, Austin Powder Company multi-purpose bulk truck (MBT)was traveling northbound on County Road 25 in rural Marshall county Alabama.  The truck was loaded with bulk amounts of ammonium nitrate prill (UN1942), as well as ammonium nitrate emulsion (UN3375), and a tank containing 200 gallons of fuel oil (NA1993).  Packaged boosters (UN0042), and detonators (UN0245) were overpacked in an IME box on either side of the truck.   The truck left the road, traveling a short  distance on the shoulder.  The driver then attempted to get the truck back on the road, during which time he crossed a small portion of the road that was an embankment (over a culvert), which caused the vehicle to lose control.  The driver then attempted to get the vehicle back under control, but in doing so the truck over-corrected, causing it to overturn on the driver's side.  The vehicle slid for roughly 100 feet before it came to rest on the driver's side, perpendicular to the street.  Ammonium nitrate prill began to slowly leak from 2 of the bins, collecting on the street.  Nothing mechanically failed on these bins.  They simply leaked due to the fact that the truck was on its side. Also, a small amount of diesel fuel (a few gallons) leaked from the saddle tanks, mixing with the spilled nitrate.  First responders arrived shortly thereafter, as did a third-party spill crew dispatched by the shipper/carrier. The material was slowly leaking from the package for roughly 2 hours.  A total of around 1,000 pounds of material leaked.  The spill was completely cleaned up within roughly 3 hours. The driver had to be cut out of the vehicle, and was life flighted to a hospital for treatment of serious injuries.
column169: If the driver returns to service, he will receive retraining prior to driving again, per policy and per requirements outlined in IME SLP-23. We have also retained a third-party accident reconstructionist, who has completed an in-depth report. The driver is still in the hospital at present, and largely unable to communicate, so we have been unable to interview him to help us in assigning a root cause to the accident.      Interviews were done with co-workers including one who witnessed the accident.  We  looked at his recent driver logs, studied mechanical and maintenance data on the truck, and generally reviewed the events of the day to better determine what may have contributed to the event.  However, until we interview the driver it will be difficult to arrive at a root cause, and therefore prescribe a course of action.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the unloading operation  the pallet of drums was placed on uneven concrete floor.  As the forklift operator approached the pallet, the fork struck the drum.  The operator immediately stopped work and placed the drum on its side, halting the leak.    Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: The root cause of the incident was determined to be unsafe forklift operation, a review of the incident and the unsafe practices was immediately reviewed with CHES.  The operator was removed and retrained before he was able to operate the forklift.

column168: On June 5, 2017, L58271-05 was southbound on Geismar yard track 1C and derailed 12 railcars.  ECUX 882437 (L / plastic pellets), CITX 703099 (L/ Plastic pellets), ECUX 882164 (L/ Plastic pellets), ECUX 845000 (L/ Plastic pellets), UTLX 647008 (L/ UN 2218 / Acrylic Acid), SHPX 210508 (L / Environmentally Sensitive), TELX 40028 (L/ UN 2218 / Acrylic Acid), DUPX 16177 (Cleaned and purged), UTLX 953626 (R/ UN 1010 / Butadienes) UTLX 642800 (   ), UTLX 640762 (L/ UN 1993 / Flammable Liquid N.O.S.), ACFX 38177 (L/ Plastic Pellets).  All appropriate departments were notified.  A drip leak was discovered from the bottom outlet flange of UTLX 640762.  The leak was unable to be stopped.  The contents of UTLX 640762 was transferred by trucks and delivered back to the shipper.  No other leaks were discovered.  UTLX 647008 was transferred into UTLX 665745.  TELX 40028 was transferred into UTLX 665750. SHPX 210508 was transferred into GATX 61446.  All transferred loads continued onto destination.  All derailed railcars were cleaned and purged then released to CN Mechanical for final disposition.  The cause of the derailment was determined to be track related issue.

column168: A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Nor was there evidence of damage or leaking while in temporary storage.  Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Material polymerized inside car while constructively placed in the rail yard, causing pressure build-up resulting in venting to atmosphere and some spillage. The car was discovered by a Norfolk Southern crew operating through the yard, then notified the train dispatcher and North Shore Railroad Operations Dept. A hazmat trained North Shore supervisor and Rail Security Coordinator where immediately dispatched to the site. The local Fire Dept., Northridge Group Emergency Response, Federal Railroad Administration Inspector and Norfolk Southern Hazmat Team were all present on site and involved in the remediation. The pressure relief valve seal ruptured due to the unknown cause of polymerization of product while inside the car. Once the car was finished venting to atmosphere, the ground clean-up commenced. The Norfolk Southern Mainline adjacent to the Lock Haven yard was closed for 12 hours before re-opening to train traffic.
column169: The receiver will unload all the product currently placed in Lock Haven Yard. Since this is a chemical reaction occurring within the car, I have no further recommendations. This incident was handled according to our Emergency Response Plan without issue.

column168: While waiting to unload, a slow minor drip from the tank gauge was observed by facility personnel. column162: SVP, TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE AND HEALTH & SAFETY
column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 1 quart of material had  escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column168: WAS CALLED TO PD-3 FOR A LEAKING HAZ-MAT. RESPONDED IN FULL PPE CLEANED UP THE AREA AND TOOK IT BACK TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING

WENT TO GO DO A SET OF HAZMAT PAPERS ON A PACKAGE IN THE WEST. UPON ARRIVAL, I NOTICED THAT ONE SIDE OF THE BOX WAS WET, IT HAD BEEN LAYING ON IT'S SIDE AT SOME POINT. CONTAINERIZED MATERIAL AND TRANSPORTED TO HAZMAT FOR PROCESSING.
UPON INSPECTION OF LEAKING PACKAGE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO LOOSE PLASTIC CAPS ON GLASS BOTTLES

DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS FOUND LOADED ON ITS SIDE INSIDEW A WALL OF PACKAGES. RESPONDER FOLLOWED PREOPER PROCEDURE AND SECURE THE PACKAGE TO MOVE TO THE SERVICE CENTER FOR PROCESSING
column169: REVIEW WITH LOADERS THE PROPER METHODS FOR LOADING HAZARDOUS PACKAGES. ON FLOOR WITH THE ORIENTATION ARROWS UP. REVIEW WITH THE SHIPPER TO SECURE CAPS PREIOR TO SHIPPING.

column168: RESPONDER WAS DISPATCHED TO A LEAKING HAZMAT, IN THE WEST PRIMARY, AT BAY 31. column168: The driver of a loaded truck and trailer combination performed a hard braking maneuver to avoid colliding with a car entering the highway from a side street. During this hard braking event, the driver heard and felt the load shift. He immediately pulled over to a safe location to do a load integrity check, during which he smelled an odor coming from the trailer. The driver closed the trailer, and immediately reported a suspected release to his management. An emergency response team was dispatched to the scene. While wearing the correct personal protective equipment, the team entered the trailer to discover one drum had suffered a small release due to damage sustained during the hard braking event. The drum that had the release was over-packed, as well as several other dented but structurally intact drums, all damaged during the hard braking event. The load continued on to its final destination without incident.     The release was reported to the PA DEP report line at 15:05 on 06/8/17.
column169: The driver was not allowed to directly supervise or be present for the building and securement of this load; it was handled by the generator’s facility personnel. The driver could only visually inspect and secure the rearmost part of the load. For myriad safety reasons, drivers are not permitted to walk on top of loads to verify proper securement; the driver was only able to effectively visually inspect the rear of the load. This load was not properly secured at intervals throughout the trailer and did not have sufficient dunnage to fill void spaces, leading to a damaging load shift under hard braking.     The generator has been consulted on this event, and asked to retrain facility personnel on proper load securement and use of dunnage to prevent any movement of packages in transportation in the future. The driver has been retrained on the need to supervise as closely as possible the load building and securement of all loads he will transport, and how to better ascertain the state of a load's securement through thorough and specific questioning of facility personnel where possible.The driver has also been retrained on when to ask to have a load rebuilt if the load securement is in doubt, or cannot be verified by the facility.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: A 40 yard roll-off box was staged in a 10 day transfer facility containment area. Upon loading of box, as it was lifted onto the transport vehicle, the sludge material flowed to the rear of the box, overtopping the rear gate and spilling into the containment area. The material had phase separated during transport releasing free liquid. An internal response team was dispatched to remediate the area. Crew donned proper PPE and assessed the site. Site was remediated effectively and all waste was containerized compliantly. Waste was shipped to final destination disposal facility without further incident. Utah DEQ notified and state report #13034 was generated by operator Deborah Ng.
column169: Corporate and local management proceeded with investigative conference calls. Direct communication and guidance with onsite personnel loading the boxes, educating them on what is acceptable material to haul in roll-off containers. Educated driving teams on proper pre trip container inspections to prevent further incidents. Executive management staffs of both motor carrier and generator, actively worked together to create a new operating procedure involving adding more solidifying agents to ensure waste stream remains solid in transport, thus nullifying phase shifting. Suspended current disposal profile and required generator re-certify waste stream as a new profile using more solidifying agents.

column162: SVP, TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE AND HEALTH & SAFETY
column168: A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the holding operation, it was discovered that approximately 30 gallons of material had escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to transfer the material into drums.  In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used in the clean-up efforts were collected and placed into the suitable drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.  Although it is hard to say what exactly caused the leak, it appears the tote was rubbing against the steel frame for too long which eventually cause a small crack to the poly tank.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container before it is loaded and during staging period as well.   And will continue to take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column168: On June 28, 2017 during unloading operations, terminal personnel discovered that (1) 55-gallon steel drum of UN1760 "pH Adjsuter" had a loose bung ring on the lid of the drum which caused approximately 1-quart to release. A contractor was dispatched who contained, neutralized, and cleaned the release by utilizing granular absorbents and lemon juice. The bung ring was replaced and the impacted debris was overpacked and staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: On June 28, 2017, during unloading operations, terminal personnel accident punctured a (1) 15-gallon poly drum containing UN1778, Fluorosilicic Acid, 8, PG II, during a forklift accident. Approximately all 15-gallons released to the concrete dock floor. A contractor was dispatched who contained, cleaned, and neutralized the release by utilizing granular absorbents and Soda Ash solution. The damaged drum and impacted debris was properly containerized and staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

On 06/26/2017 at 2044 hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Bedford Park FL Terminal discovered SNLU157862, a loaded container of 13pcs UN3109, Organic Peroxide Type F Liquid (peroxyacetic acid type f stabilized), 5.2, in 200 gallon plastic totes with aluminum cage, leaked less than 5 gals of liquid from rear of container with minimal amount onto asphalt pavement. The container was isolated and NRC was notified, report#1182366. The shipper, Schneider National Inc, representative was notified by CSXI Customer Service, case#340883. CSXT emergency response contractor, SUNPRO Services, was dispatched to the scene and found one 200 gallon tote released less than 5 gallons of product due to being punctured on bottom corner. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the leak by transfer of product into recovery tote, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the release site. The original freight container with proper load/block/brace was released to the shipper.     This incident did not require a special switching move.   This incident did not require a Form 7.1..
Associate did not block and/or brace freight properly for transport.  Freight was crushed causing release of product.

column168: Jacksonville, FL – 6/26/2017 – GPPX 960002 – Flammable Liquids N.O.S.      On 6/26/2017 at 11:55, in Edgewood Yard, Jacksonville, FL, Kenneth Barefield, FRA Hazardous Material Inspector, discovered GPPX 960002, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids N.O.S (Spirits of Turpentine), leaking from the liquid line valve secondary closure cap due to an overloaded tank car.  The car was isolated and the shipper Georgia-Pacific and the NRC (report number 1182309) were notified.  CHEMTREC report number  2017-06-26-00120.  Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking from the liquid line.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Regina Ehrhardt, phone number 770-329-0562).  Contractor personnel offloaded the proper amount for one percent of the product and decontaminated the car.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.  This incident did not require a special switching move or a 7.1.
column169: NARRI cause Code - 662 - car was overfilled with product, release from Liquid line valve, plug was less than tool tight

column168: Our driver was unloading the CTMV and the product transfer hose ruptured near the connection to the CTMV. The driver immediately deployed the emergency shut off to stop the product flow. The release is estimated to have been less than five minutes.   It was discovered that a valve on the consignee's intake line was closed in the middle of the unloading process, creating excess pressure that caused the product transfer hose to rupture.     Our event # 65028

Carrier had started unloading when approximately 1 pint of product spilled from the external valve, at the fittings.  Carrier stopped the pump, stopping the flow of product.    Carrier driver tightened up the fittings, and used shims to stop the leaking.    The duration of the release was about 4 to 5 minutes.  Consignee assisted with cleanup, using spill pads.  Spill was within their contained area.    Event 65087

column168: At approximately 13:09 Tuesday, June 13, 2017, a driver pulled over to do a routine tire and load check of his loaded tractor trailer and discovered he had a release from the rear of his trailer. He shortly after discovered leaking from the front of the trailer as well. The driver notified his management and the local authorities immediately. In addition, the driver took immediate steps to contain the release, using a shovel to create a berm for containment.      The State of Vermont and the NRC were notified of the release. The State of Vermont DEC sent Ted Unkles to the scene to assist in the cleanup efforts. The EPA sent Ted Bazenas to the scene to assist in the cleanup efforts. The release and subsequent cleanup and remediation efforts were monitored by the Vermont DEC, the EPA, and the US DOT. The release and subsequent cleanup and remediation efforts were monitored by the Vermont DEC, the EPA, and the US DOT.      The police, local fire department, and hazardous materials response team responded to the scene and coordinated cleanup efforts. Clean Harbors dispatched a field services crew with the correct personal protective equipment to complete the discovery, cleanup, and site remediation. After the source of the release was identified, the other waste drums and totes of this load were decontaminated, loaded onto a trailer, and continued to their intended destination.     The release cleanup closed the roadway VT-103 in both directions from approximately 13:30 6/13/2017 to 11:00 6/14/2017.      It was determined that the polyethylene non-bulk package was punctured by a nail head that extended above the flat surface of the pallet on which the container was situated.
column169: We will work with the client to ensure all drummed outgoing waste utilize only carefully inspected pallets in defect free condition, and care is taken in the placement of drums on those pallets. The driver will be retrained in load condition inspection, to include a closer inspection of the pallet condition and load placement on the pallets (where practicable).

column168: Release was discovered as the Veolia driver was leaving Veolia's 10-Day in transportation yard located in Phoenix, AZ. Less than 2 gallons of material was released to the trailer interior, less than 1 gallon was released to the asphalt. Two drums containing solid filter cake material with entrained liquids were filled to the top.  The entrained liquids rose to the top during transportation due to pressurization caused by a change in temperature resulting in a release from the filling closure. Spilled liquids were cleaned up and the 2 leaking drums were packaged into salvage drums to alleviate future problems. Other drums on the shipment were inspected and were deemed to be properly packaged and did not pose a transportation risk.
column169: Reinforcement of packaging training in regards to filling a container to allow expansion space and verification of the potential amount of entrained liquids with containers that may rise to surface during transportation. Notification has been made to the customer to allow adequate headspace in filter cake drums.

column168: On 6/28/17 at approximately 5:25 pm a Linden Bulk truck had just finished loading Ethyl Acrylate from the IMTT Chem South loading rack when an IMTT Chemical Operations Supervisor detected an odor near the truck.  Upon investigation he discovered that there was liquid product inside the crash box on the top of the tanker compartment.  The driver was questioned and it was determined that the wash out cap on the truck's vapor return line was missing.  The IMTT Chemical Operator asked the driver if he had a replacement gasket which he did and it was subsequently installed.  The driver was then asked to tighten the fittings on the dome lid.  US Ecology (IMTT's OSRO) was contacted to come to the area and wash out the Ethyl Acrylate from the truck's crash box area.  The truck was permitted to leave after it was determined that the leak had been addressed and no odor was being emitted.
column169: IMTT personnel followed all proper procedures and is not responsible for defective components on the third party transporter's equipment. The  customer of the product was contacted and told of the incident. The customer will follow up with the transporter to address any mechanical or  structural issues with the truck or related components.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: A 40 yard roll-off box was staged in a 10 day transfer facility containment area. Upon loading of box, as it was lifted onto the transport vehicle, the  sludge material flowed to the rear of the box, overtopping the rear gate and spilling into the containment area. The material had phase separated  during transport releasing free liquid. An internal response team was dispatched to remediate the area. Crew donned proper PPE and assessed the site.  Site was remediated effectively and all waste was containerized compliantly. Waste was shipped to final destination disposal facility without further  incident. Utah DEQ notified and state report #13037 was generated by operator Deborah Ng.
column169: Corporate and local management proceeded with investigative conference calls. Direct communication and guidance with onsite personnel loading the  boxes, educating them on what is acceptable material to haul in roll-off containers. Educated driving teams on proper pre trip container inspections to  prevent further incidents. Executive management staffs of both motor carrier and generator, actively worked together to create a new operating  procedure involving adding more solidifying agents to ensure waste stream remains solid in transport, thus nullifying phase shifting. Suspended current  disposal profile and required generator re-certify waste stream as a new profile using more solidifying agents.

column168: METRO UNLOAD SUPERVISOR BROUGHT A PLASTIC TOTE TO A HAZMAT AUDITOR. THE TOTE WAS VIBRATING AND THE SOUND OF ACTIVATED MACHINERY WAS COMING FROM INSIDE. THE LID OF THE TOTE WAS PADLOCKED ON TWO CORNERS, BUT THE AUDITOR WAS ABLE TO PRY OPEN A CORNER. MANY MISCELLANEOUS ITEMS WERE INSIDE, AND THE AUDITOR HAD TO RUMMAGE AROUND INSIDE BEFORE FINDING A CORDLESS DRILL THAT HAD TURNED ON DURING TRANSPORT. A QUICK INVENTORY OF THE CONTENTS REVEALED TWO LITHIUM ION BATTERY POWERED DRILLS, A PROPANE FUEL CYLINDER, AND A METAL CAN WITH FLAMMABLE LIQUID WARNINGS. HMSC WAS CONTACTED AND HELPDESK RULED: TREAT AS UNDECLARED AND HOLD PENDING REGULATORY INVESTIGATION. SUBSEQUENT CATALOGING OF THE CONTENTS REVEALED TWO OTHER POSSIBLE HAZMAT ITEMS: A SPRAY BOTTLE MARKED "ALCHEHOL" (ALCOHOL?) WITH A CLEAR LIQUID INSIDE; AND A SPRAY BOTTLE, UNMARKED, WITH A BLUE LIQUID INSIDE. ALL OTHER CONTENTS ARE NON-HAZARDOUS (VARIOUS TOOLS, SUPPLIES, ETC).

column168: WHILE IN TRANSIT TO CUSTOMER SITE, MAXAM BULK VEHICLE TRANSPORTING AN PRILL STRUCK A LARGE DEFORMITY IN ROADWAY CAUSING RIGHT REAR SUSPENSION TO FAIL RESULTING IN LOSS OF VEHICLE CONTROL AND ROLLOVER WITH SPILLAGE OF 500 POUNDS (225 KGS) OF AN PRILL AND 10 GALLONS (40 LITTERS) OF DISEL FUEL FROM VEHICLE SADDLE TANK.     MAXAM DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED. A SECOND MAXAM EMPLOYEE IN A FOLLOWING VEHICLE WITNESSED THE INCIDENT. THE TN STATE POLICE, TN EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY, TN DOT, LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO SCENE.    UNDER TNEMA DIRECTION AND APPROVAL, THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR REMOVED SPILLED AND DIESEL AND LADING REMAINING IN VEHICLE USING VACUUM AND ABSORBENTS, AND THE AREA WAS WASHED DOWN BY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.     AS CONFIRMED BY TDOT, A LARGE DEFORMITY (POTHOLE) AT THE BRIDGE DECK AND ROADWAY TRANSITION CAUSED RIGHT REAR SUSPENSION TO FAIL. TDOT COMMENTED THAT ANOTHER COMMERCIAL VEHICLE EXPERIENCE A SIMILAR ISSUE AT THIS LOCATION SEVERAL WEEKS EARLIER.

column168: THE DELIVERY DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO DELIVER TO LAFARGE CEMENT I RAVENA NY ON 6/26. HE ARRIVED AT THE DELIVERY LOCATION AROUND 0830 ON 6/26. HE CALLED THE CONTROL ROOM FOR VERIFICATION THAT THE STORAGE TANK WOULD HOLD THE 6,000 GALLON DELIVERY. THEY CONFIRMED THAT THEY WERE AT 52% AND THERE WAS ENOUGH ROOM TO TAKE THE DELIVERY. THEY OPENED THE AUTO VALVES AFTER VERIFICATION AND THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO START TO HOOK UP HOSES. AFTER ALL HOSES ARE HOOKED UP. HE OPENED UP THE RECEIVING TANK VALVES AND THE CTMV VALVES. HE STARTED THE UNLOADING PROCESS. AFTER PUMPING APPROXIMATELY 40 MINUTES HE HEARD THE PUMP MAKE A DIFFERENT NOISE AND HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE TRANSFER BY USE OF THE BASE SYSTEM. THE BASE SYSTEM SHUTS DOWN THE INTERNAL AND THE PUMP BY ORDER OF A REMOTE. HE CALLED THE CONTROL ROOM AND ADVISED THEM THAT THE TANK IS OVERFILLED. THEY HAD INDICATED THAT IT WAS NOT THEY ARE AT 68%. THE HIGH LEVEL ALARMS WAS NOT REACHED SO THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF POSSIBLE OVERFILL. THEY SENT DOWN SAFETY OPERATORS AND BY THAT TIME THERE WAS A TRICKLE OF AQUA COMING OUT OF THE RELEASE DEVICE ON THE STORAGE TANK RESULTING IN ABOUT 2 GALLON RELEASE INTO THE AQUA CONTAINMENT AREA. THE FIXED LEVEL GAUGE COULD NOT BE VIEWED SO THEY CUT A HOLE IN THE WALL AND FOUND THAT TO BE 68% ALSO. AFTER THAT THEY LET THE DRIVER UNHOOK AND RETURN WITH APPROXIMATELY 1,500 GALLONS ON THE CTMV.
column169: THE SONAR GAUGE WAS RE-CALIBRATED AND THE FIXED LEVEL GAUGE WAS INSTALLED WRONG AND WAS REMOVED AND INSTALLED CORRECTLY. WE KNOW HAVE 3 POINTS THAT THE LEVEL GAUGE CAN BE VIEWED.

column168: Material Handler picked up the drum which failed using a drum grabber attachment on a forklift. When he lifted the drum and began moving backward the bottom of the drum failed releasing the contents onto the warehouse floor. Warehouse personnel donned appropriate PPE and cleaned up the spilled material, placing it and the damaged drum into a poly over pack drum. Warehouse personnel also over packed the remaining 3 drums on the shipment. 1 of the remaining drums showed signs of possible failure and the remaining 2 were over packed as a precaution as they contained the same material. The material was shipped to it's final destination without further incident.
column169: It is believed that an unidentified substance already present when the material was loaded reacted with the material causing the failure. Discussions were held with the generator who has agreed that future shipments of this material will be transported in poly drums. Further drums will be more closely inspected prior to loading. Finally, drivers have been instructed to closely check all containers for any sign of reaction or failure.

column168: WHILE TRAVELING ON THE I5 NB TUCK LANE, GOING APPROX 21 MPH WITH FLASHER ON, THE STOP ENGINE LIGHT CAME ON AND DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER TO THE LEFT RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD. TURNED ENGINE OFF AND WENT TO INSPECT THE ENGINE. DRIVER AS EXITING THROUGH THE PASSENGER DOOR, NOTICED WHITE SMOKED COMING FROM THE ENGINE COMPARTMENT WHILE OPENING THE HOOD, DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL FLAME COMING FROM THE DRIVER SIDE OF THE ENGINE, DRIVER WENT TO RETRIEVE TRUCK FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND ATTEMPTED TO PUT OUT THE FIRE. THE FIRE BECAME LARGER AND OUT OF CONTROL. WHEN THE EXTINGUISHER WAS EXHAUSTED, I RETURNED TO THE TRUCK AND TOOK WHAT I COULD, AND RAN AS FAR AS POSSIBLY AND CALLED 911. WHEN RESPONDERS ARRIVE THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE SEVERELY BURNED & DAMAGES CLEAN HARBORS WERE CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE AREA.
column169: ALL COMPANY FLEET WERE REINSPECTED FOR UNSAFE HAZARD AND ALL DRIVER RETRAINED ON PRE POST INSPECTIONS AND APPLY MORE TAILGATE MEETINGS.

column168: When the local train crew was making a pickup in the Hickory Siding, they noticed an odor coming from PROX 300144.  They notified the WLE Dispatcher who then called me, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  I then called Specialized Professional Services Inc. out of Washington, PA to respond to the leak.  When they arrived, they noticed that the base bolts on the liquid valve were extremely loose and they were able to move the valve from side to side.  They also looked at the manway lid gasket and found that it was deteriorated.  They vapor leak was coming from two separate areas of the car.  They tightened the vapor valve and replaced the manway gasket and we then sent the car to our Rook Yard in Carnegie, PA where the car will be bubble tested before it is released for service.

column168: One employee working along was attaching an electric match to the ematch receptacle on a 4" shell.  The ematch appeared to ignite causing the shell to explode.  The shell was in a cardboard box with other shells, the employee lifted it onto a table where she held it while inserting the electric match (ignitor).  No package failed, there was no release of toxic substances.  The employees' hands were severely injured requiring surgery and skin grafts.  She is recovering now.
column169: The head of the electric match is made from a chemical composition that is somewhat friction and impact sensitive.  Employees are trained to not pull back the plastic protective shroud over the head of the match and not to subject the match head to friction or impact of any sort.  We are producing updated training material now to re-stress these points.  At times, a strand of black match (cotton twine impregnated with black powder) can be found in the receptacle that the match is inserted into.  We are procuring a non-sparking tool to push this blackmatch down to the bottom of the receptacle to insure that the head of the ematch has little chance to come into contact with it, to further reduce the chance of any friction on the head of any sort.  At times, the plastic protective shroud over the ematch head can be dislodged or pulled back.  We are likely to switch to a US ematch producer who provides an ematch with a shroud that cannot be pulled back.

column25: The Lubrizol Corp (s/b: South Coast Terminals Plant 5)
column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: At approximately 10:50 PST on 6/29/17, the UTLX 649774 was found to be leaking from the top of the car during an inbound roll-by inspection in the Barstow yard.  The car was isolated and BNSF Hazmat responders assessed the release finding it not actively leaking but with wetness from the Vacuum Relief Valve which was threaded into the manway lid.  Responders vented and opened the tank car to inspect the VRV and found the VRV o-ring gasket was no longer sealing and had appeared to have expanded from its original sealing area.  The VRV was temporarily secured until the car could be placed on a repair track to have the valve removed and a plug installed in its place.  The plug was installed on 7/5/17.  No leaking material reached the ground, the approximately 1/2 gallon released from the car was isolated entirely to the car body.  The BNSF Hazmat team cleaned the residue from the car with rags and degreaser.  Lubrizol provided an OTMA for movement of the car to Destination in Richmond, CA for unloading and a seperate OTMA for movement to shop once unloaded.
column169: The shipper has been notified of the defective valve.  Additional investigation should be conducted by the shipper to determine the root cause of this incident including human and mechanical factors that may have contributed to the release.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On June 30, 2017 at approximately 19:55, the Stockton Hub Operations team reported unit RDWY558052 to have a leaking condition upon deramp. The rail waybill indicated hazardous commodity within the trailer, therefore the unit was move to the containment area and Hazmat One was contacted to dispatch an approved hazmat contractor, NRC Environmental.  Upon investigation significant cargo shift was observed when the trailer door was opened. No securement was observed during the leak investigation and remediation. The leak was determined to involve 4 1-gallon pails of "Crystal Clear Epoxy" -UN2735 (amines) which were located on the right side of the trailer, on the bottom layer stretchwrapped and palletized. The pails were crushed by the cargo stacked on top of the pails.  The spill was remediated and unit was released to move outgate.  Waste materials were consolidated into appropriate DOT containers and were transported by NRC Environmental for appropriate profiling and disposal under the direction of Hazmat One and the generator.
column169: The shipper should ensure that appropriate blocking and bracing practices are utilized to prevent cargo shift and damage to containers during transport.  BNSF LARS has followed up with the shipper for corrective measures.

column168: There was no package failure.  While unloading the CTMV, the consignee's above ground storage tank overflowed.  The duration of the release occurred no longer than 30 seconds.  The hazmat release ceases when the driver turned the CTMV transfer pump off.  Absorbents were placed on the spill.             Quality Event #65156.

A veteran tank driver with Schneider stopped at a truck stop.  He'd been checking his washout caps at every stop and tapping them.  One however ended up working its way slightly loose and a small amount of product seeped out.  Nothing was dripping off of the trailer.  Driver inspected the cap and found that the cap, the threading on the cap, and the gasket all appeared to be in good condition.  He re-tightened it down and zip tied them to ensure very minimal movement if they started to loosen again.
column169: I believe this will be an isolated incident with this driver.  He has 20+ on record for Schneider with a very clean record and goes by the book as safety is concerned. He will be ensuring he zip ties all washout caps before departing the shipper.

Carrier off loading CTMV into consignee tank.  The consignee tank spilled product from a vent on top of their tank.  Spill was contained within the concrete area at consignee.    The duration of the release was about 5 minutes.  Consignee employees did cleanup.    Event 65164

Unit 1 (Pick Up Truck) and Unit 2 (CRCT Transport Vehicle) were traveling northbound on state highway 11.  Unit 2 activated left turn signal approximately 1/4 mile prior to turning left into private lease road.  As unit 2 began to turn left, unit 1 attempted to pass on the left side of unit 2 colliding as unit 2 was turning into the private lease road. When unit 1 collided with unit 2 it damaged the under piping of unit 2 cargo trailer thus allowing approximately 25 gallons of crude oil to be released.  Approximately 20 gallons were contained in buckets and the remaining 5 gallons spilled onto the highway and spread towards the adjacent private drive area.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON JUNE 30TH, OUR DRIVER WAS COMING OFF HIS BREAK AND PERFORMED A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION ON HIS TRAILER IN A VACANT PARKING LOT. HE WENT TO THE EXTERNAL VALVE ON THE TRAILER AND RE-POSITIONED THE CLAMP ON IT. IN DOING SO, THE DRIVER HAD A MISHAP AND PRODUCT RELEASED OUT OF THE VALVE AND ONTO THE GROUND. (ASPHALT SURFACE) IT IS ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN 15 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY THREW DOWN ABSORBENT PADS AND CONTAINED THE SPILL TO THE BEST OF HIS ABILITY. NO STORM DRAINS OR WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. AN OUTSIDE CLEAN-UP CREW (ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCT SERVICES OF VERMONT) WAS CALLED IN AND THEY THREW SPEEDY DRY ON THE PRODUCT THAT WAS RELEASED AND COLLECTED IT UP AND DISPOSED OF IT.
column169: THIS SPILL WAS AN ACCIDENT AND OCCURRED DUE TO THE DRIVER ERROR. THE DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW COMPANY POLICY AND WAS HANDLING A VALVE INAPPROPRIATELY AND WITHOUT A BUCKET BEING IN PLACE. IMMEDIATELY AFTER THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED, THE DRIVER WAS BOUGHT INTO THE OFFICE AND RE-TRAINED ON THE PROPER HANDLING PROCEDURES. AS A LEARNING TOOL WE WILL INFORM ALL OF OUR DRIVERS ABOUT THIS INCIDENT VIA A MEMO IN THEIR PAYCHECKS. THIS MEMO WILL ALERT THEM OF WHAT HAPPENED AND STRESS THE IMPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING COMPANY POLICY FOR HANDLING VALVES ON THE TRAILER.

column162: SVP, TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE AND HEALTH & SAFETY
column168: During loading operations, a Safety Kleen driver noted the drum being picked up did not have a ring.  Driver placed a ring on the drum and proceeded to move the drum down a steep hill.  While doing so, a small amount of material escaped.  Driver and co-driver determined to then over-pack the drum.  During this process approximately 15 gallons of material escaped.  The material spilled was immediately contained.  Absorbent material was applied to the spilled material and area. Drum was then successfully over packed. All absorbent and spill debris was placed in the over  pack drum and secured for shipment to the designated treatment facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, evidence of missing ring was observed and attempt was made to provide ring to drum.  Driver did not have the proper ring, which compounded the situation.  Driver should have never accepted the drum for transport.  The shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all containers used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.  Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as  before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. Drivers will carry manufacturer drum closure instructions.  Should they not have the correct material they are instructed to deny the transport.  Additionally driver will be retrained in over-packing procedures.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT THE LOST CREEK ISR PROJECT FACILITY DURING THE LOADING OF DRUMS INTO A CONTRACT CARRIER CONVEYANCE (53 FOOT ENCLOSED CARGO TRAILER) VIA FORKLIFT FITTED WITH A DRUM CARRYING APPARATUS. THE HEATH PHYSICS TECHNICIAN (HPT) AND TWO MAINTENANCE WORKERS WERE INVOLVED IN THE LOADING OPERATION OF PACKAGED URANIUM YELLOWCAKE (U3O8, 1A2 DRUMS, LOT # LC-060D). THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR (MAINTENANCE WORKER CERTIFIED ON FORKLIFT) WAS POSITIONING A DRUM BETWEEN THE TRAILER WALL AND ANOTHER LOADED DRUM WITH THE FORKLIFT WHEN THE DRUM CARRYING APPARATUS ACCIDENTALLY STRUCK THE ADJACENT DRUM CAUSING A RUPTURE. YELLOWCAKE WITHIN THE DRUM WAS RELEASED AND A SMALL AMOUNT SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER DECK. THE LINEAR RUPTURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2-3 INCHES AT THE APPROXIMATE MIDPOINT OF THE SIDE OF THE DRUM. SEE ATTACHED FIGURES 1 AND 2.  THE RUPTURED PACKAGE WAS DRUM #33, WITH A GROSS WEIGHT OF 871.5 LBS, AND A NET WEIGHT OF YELLOWCAKE OF 828.5 LBS. THIS BARREL WAS THE SEVENTH (7TH) BARREL LOADED AND THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WHILE LOADING AND POSITIONING THE EIGHT (8TH) BARREL ON THE CONVEYANCE. THE RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER (RSO) AND HPT WERE CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE SPILL. THE BREACH WAS IMMEDIATELY COVERED WITH ADHESIVE TAPE BY THE MAINTENANCE WORKER UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE HPT TO PREVENT AND ADDITIONAL SPILLAGE. THE RSO ESTIMATED A MAXIMUM TOTAL OF 0.5. LBS OF YELLOWCAKE SPILLED IN THE TRAILER. THE SPILL OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 1045 HRS INSIDE OF THE TRAILER. THE CONTRACT CARRIER WAS NOT ON-SITE DURING LOADING, THE INCIDENT, OR DURING THE CLEANUP PROCESS.   NOTIFICATION TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS MADE VIA TELEPHONE AT APPROXIMATELY 1230 HRS. NOTIFICATION WAS ALSO MADE TO THE NUCLEAR REGULATORY COMMISSION PROJECT MANAGER VIA PHONE AND EMAIL THIS AFTERNOON. THE RSO AND HPT CONDUCTED CLEANUP AS AUTHORIZED BY A RADIATION WORK PERMIT AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HRS. CALCULATED DOSE RESULTS FROM THE AIR SAMPLES SHOWED NO SIGNIFICANT DOSE (ALL <100MREM 24HR) AND THE RESULTS WERE REPORTED TO NRC OPERATIONS CENTER AND NRC REGION IV. NO ADDITIONAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE REQUIRED UNDER 10 CFR 20.2202 AND 2203 AS A RESULT.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTIONS AND REPORTING INCLUDES THE FOLLOWING:  1. PROVIDE A SPOTTER WITHIN THE TRAILER DURING LOADING AS FEASIBLE AND ONLY IF IT IS SAFE TO DO SO.   2. EVALUATE DIFFERENT TYPES OF DRUM CARRYING APPARATUS FOR THE FORKLIFT TO DETERMINE IF THERE IS A MORE APPROPRIATE STYLE OF DRUM CARRIER.  3. PROVIDE A 30 DAY REPORT TO DOT PHMSA (49 CFR 171.16) AND NRC HEADQUARTERS (NRC LICENSE CONDITION 11.6)

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED. THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL (FCE) WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. FCE ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE TOTE. FCE DISCOVERED A SMALL PUDDLE OF PRODUCT AND STAINING BELOW THE TOTE VALVE. THE TOP OF THE TOTE WAS ALSO IMPACTED BY PRODUCT AND THE CAP WAS LOOSE. APPROXIMATELY 11 LITERS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. FCE UTILIZED ABSORBENT PADS TO CLEANUP THE IMPACTED TOTE. THE CONTENTS OF THE TOTE WAS TRANSFERRED INTO FIVE (5) 55-GALLON DRUMS. FCE UTILIZED ABSORBENT PADS TO CLEAN THE EMPTY TOTE. FIVE (5) 55-GALLON DRUMS OF PRODUCT AND ONE(1) EMPTY TOTE WERE LEFT AT THE SITE. ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM OF WASTE WAS GENERATED AND TRANSPORTED BY FCE TO THEIR FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL COORDINATION.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO ACTION HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER MUSKET TRANSPORT WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED PACKAGE CAME IN AND WAS TAKEN OUT FOR DELIVERY. THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED THE SHIPMENT AS THEY SUSPECTED IT HAD BEEN SHIPPED INCORRECTLY, AS IT WAS NOT LABELED OR MARKED AS DANGEROUS GOODS. SO WE BROUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK AND OPENED IT TO FIND SOME FUEL PUMP FOR AN AIRPLANE WITH AN ODOR. I CONTACTED DEBORAH KENNEDY (ATL/FAA), AT 15:25 ON 6-26-2017 OF THE TO ADVISE OF THE INCIDENT SO THAT SHE COULD ASSIGN SOMEONE TO GO AND VIEW THE PACKAGE LATER ON. THE FAA SAW THE PACKAGE ON 6-28-2017 AND RELEASED THE SHIPMENT. I’M TRYING TO WORK WITH THE SHIPPER TO PROVIDE SOME DG P/W, OR TO SEE IF SOMEONE ELSE CAN PICK THE SHIPMENT UP. THE SHIPMENT WAS LATER RELEASED TO A PARTY THAT HAD CONTACTED ME BY THE SHIPPER.

THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND I NOTIFIED DEBORAH KENNEDY OF THE ATL/FAA ON 7-11-2017 TO REPORT THE INCIDENT THAT HAD HAPPENED ON 6-27-2017. column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap; Dropped
column168: A TEMPORARY DRIVER AND A SALES REPRESENTATIVE WERE DELIVERING PRODUCT IN A RENTAL TRUCK WITH A LIFT GATE. THIS WAS THE LAST STOP OF THE DAY. THE DRIVER WAS USING AN ELECTRIC PALLET JACK POSITIONING THE PALLET ON THE LIFT GATE TO UNLOAD. THE SALES REPRESENTATIVE STATED THAT WHEN THE DRIVER STARTED TO PUSH THE BUTTON FOR THE LIFT GATE TO LOWER, THE LIFT GATE DROPPED QUICKLY, 1 FOOT, CAUSING THE PALLET TO DROP TO THE BLACK TOP. WHEN THE BATTERIES HIT THE BLACKTOP THEY CRACKED. THE DRIVER AND THE REPRESENTATIVE STARTED SETTING THEM UPRIGHT TO MINIMIZE THE SPILLAGE. WITHIN LESS THAN 2 MINUTES ALL THE BATTERIES WERE UP RIGHTED TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE. SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID AND PLASTIC BAGS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING BATTERIES ALONG WITH THE SODA ASH.
column169: PRE-TRIP INSPECTIONS ARE DONE BY THE DRIVERS EACH MORNING BEFORE THEY GO OUT ON THE ROAD. BEING A RENTAL TRUCK, NO PAST HISTORY OF ISSUES WITH THIS VEHICLE OR REPORTS OF PROBLEM WAS KNOWN. PRIOR TO THIS INCIDENT WE HAVE REDUCED THE WEIGHT OF PRODUCT PLACED ON THE LIFT GATES WITH NO PROBLEMS SINCE.

column168: DATE AND TIME OF INCIDENT: 6/12/2017 AT 0540  TYPE OF INCIDENT: TANK RELEASE   DURATION OF INCIDENT/RELEASE: 40 MINUTES  ESTIMATED VOLUME OF RELEASE: 1333 GALLONS   DESCRIPTION OF SUBSTANCE OF CONCERN: 28% HYDROCHLORIC ACID  RELEASE CONTAINED: YES  AGRICULTURE RELATED: NO  CAUSE OF INCIDENT: BROKEN DRAIN LINE ON THE BELLY OF THE TRAILER  ACTION TAKEN AND RECOMMENDED/PLANNED FUTURE ACTION: WASH OFF THE HIGHWAY WITH WATER AND DUG UP ALL THE DIRT AROUND THE SPILL SITE AND TOOK TO LANDFILL AFTER IT WAS NEUTRALIZED. AT THE INSTRUCTION OF NDHP AND ND DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH ROADWAY WAS RINSED OFF INTO ROADSIDE DIRT/SOIL. SOIL WAS EXTRACTED FROM AREA. VOLUME @ EIGHT (8) CUBIC YARDS. MATERIAL SHOWED PH OF 3.0. LOADED IN DUMP TRUCK FOR DISPOSAL. SOIL WAS PERMITTED TO BE DISPOSED OF AT COUNTY LANDFILL.  THE TRAILER WAS EMPTIED AND RETURNED TO SHOP FOR INSPECTION. APPEARS TO BE TRAILER MECHANICAL FAILURE IN 2 AREAS:   A. THE BELLY LINE SEPARATED FROM THE FRONT TUBE OUTLET CONNECTION (1ST COMPARTMENT);   B. THE INTERNAL VALVE (“FIRE VALVE”) SHOWED CLOSED AND ENGAGED, BUT WAS NOT – THE FULL CONTENTS OF REAR COMPARTMENT EMPTIED OUT.   PLEASE SEE  ATTACHED PHOTOS.
column169: REVIEW EQUIPMENT INSPECTION PROCESS TO MAKE SURE ALL EQUIPMENT IS IN PROPER WORKING CONDITION BEFORE HAULING MATERIAL.

column168: Driver arrived at LeDanois lease location to load and was due for 30 min break. Employee worked the product tank and hooked up hoses to be prepared to load tanker trailer.  Employee took his break. Driver had truck valves closed, line valve closed, breather valve and tank valve open, PTO off. When break was finished, driver turned on the PTO to go load, when he exited the truck he saw oil spilling over the environmental box. He checked the valve again to make sure it was closed, then to the tank to close that valve. He opened my trailer valves and sucked the environmental box empty, then put oil pads out. He called the local site pumper to come help.  They notified their supervisors and reported the release.  The material was contained to the immediate area and was remediated by local personnel.  The driver failed to open the unload tank valve before starting the pump process and this was operator error.  Correcting this process entailed retraining the driver on proper procedures and not stopping mid-task to take a break.  Must continue through or not get distracted.  Learners were shared with all drivers.
column169: Driver and fellow co-workers were retrained in the proper load and unload process.  Distraction awareness is a key factor in this employee error.

column168: A BYSTANDER PULLED OUT FROM SIDE ROAD AND HIT OUR GAS TRUCK IN FRONT TIRE. THE BUMPER WAS PUSHED INTO THE TIRE CAUSING IT TO BLOW OUT. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL AND RAN OFF THE ROAD. THE TRUCK HIT TWO TIRES BEFORE OVERTURNING AND COMING TO A STOP. A TIRE DAMAGED THE TANK/COMPARTMENT HOLDING UN 1203 GASOLINE MATERIAL. APPROXIMATELY 660 GALLONS TO 729 GALLONS WERE LOST. THE TRUCK FUEL TANK WAS ALSO DAMAGED AND APPROXIMATELY 99 GALLONS WAS LOST OF NA 1993 DIESEL FUEL. A RESPONSE TEAM WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. IT TOOK ABOUT 3-4 HOURS TO CLEAN UP SITE FROM TIME OF ACCIDENT.
column169: THERE ARE NO CORRECTIONS FOR OUR DRIVER AS IT WAS NOT OUR FAULT. OUR DRIVER COULD NOT HAVE PREVENTED THE ACCIDENT.

column168: THE TANKER WAS NORTHBOUND ON STATE ROAD 65 AND EXITED THE ROADWAY TO THE EAST, LOSING CONTROL. THE TANKER STRUCK A POLE, WENT OVER A DRIVEWAY, AND OVERTURNED. THE ETHANOL BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE TANKER AND CAUGHT FIRE. THE SPILL OCCURRED APPROXIMATELY 680 FEET NORTH OF THE INTERSECTION OF STATE ROAD 65 AND COUNTY ROAD M SOUTH OF MCCLURE, OHIO. LOCATION OF SPILL WAS IN HENRY COUNTY, DAMASCUS TOWNSHIP, MCCLURE, OHIO. THE SPILL OCCURRED ON JUNE 22, 2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 P.M. BASED ON INFORMATION FROM SECORD, THE PRODUCT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED FROM POET BIOREFINING IN LEIPSIC, OHIO TO SUNOCO LOGISTICS COMPANY IN ROMULUS, MICHIGAN. THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE RELEASE ON JUNE 22, 2017. APPROXIMATELY 16,700 SQUARE FEET ON THE WESTERN SIDE OF STATE ROAD 65 AND 4,025 SQUARE FEET ON THE EASTERN SIDE OF STATE ROAD 65 WAS AFFECTED BY THE SPILL, THIS ESTIMATION INCLUDES SURFACES IMPACTED BY THE PRODUCT AND AREAS BURNT BY FIRE. STATE ROAD 65 WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 36 HOURS FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT. OHIO EPA ASSIGNED SPILL #1706EPA0000387 TO THE SPILL. APPROXIMATELY 10,900 GALLONS OF WATER WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH ON THE WESTERN SIDE OF STATE ROAD 65 AND APPROXIMATELY 287.98 TONS OF ETHANOL IMPACTED SOIL WAS REMOVED FROM FOUR AREAS DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN IMPACTED BY THE SPILL.
column169: FOLLOWING THE SPILL, SECORD FARMS REQUIRED THE DRIVER TO UNDERGO A DRIVING AND OPERATING REFRESHER PRIOR TO RETURNING TO THE JOB.

column169: Corrective Actions:    1. Procedures   a. Discussed use, care and inspection with hose vendor and referenced manufacturer recommendations to develop Chemical Hose Preventative Maintenance Program.    Components of a Preventive Maintenance Program:   • Preventive Knowledge   • Proper hose selection and application   • Proper coupling selection   • Proper attachment of couplings to hose   • Maintenance and storage guidelines    • Agency specifications Preventive Action   • Periodic inspections   • Hydrostatic pressure testing   • Scheduled replacement   • Proper hose storage   • Troubleshooting     2. Training (ongoing refresher / OJT)  a. Hazard ID & JSA  b. Chemical Hose Preventative Maintenance.    3. Communications   a. Utilize Pre Job meeting and JSA to communicate job task hazards between crewmembers and other on-site personnel.       4. Management Systems   a. Inspection Intervals & Checklist  b. Hazard ID / Assessment    5. Human Engineering   a. Preventative Maintenance training       6. Work Direction   a. Procedure – Loading / Unloading in line with manufacture recommendations.     b. Take 5 and step back to discuss best plan of action and update JSA if problems arise during work activities.       7. Supervision  a. Mentor and observe.  b. Observations to confirm training and procedure understood.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE. TRANSIT CARGO NOPIC WAS NOT SIGNED BY THE LOAD MASTER AND NOT GIVEN TO THE PIC. ON JUNE 17, INBOUND HA 51 JFK-HNL TRANSPORTED A SHIPMENT OF CLASS 9 CONSUMER COMMODITIES (ID 8000) THAT WAS MANIFESTED TO AKL, IT’S FINAL DESTINATION. THE SHIPMENT ARRIVED JUNE 17 AND TRANSITED TO HNL CARGO AWAITING TRANSPORT ON JUNE 20, VIA HA 445 HNL-AKL.   AT 0903 ON JUNE 20, THE ASSISTANT MANAGER-HNL CARGO SENT THE DAILY CARGO OPS EMAIL TO LOAD CONTROL AND RAMP CHIEFS STATING THAT THERE WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS (DG) SHIPMENT FOR HA 445. DURING THE MORNING BRIEFING CALL, CARGO VERBALLY CONFIRMED THERE WAS A DG SHIPMENT FOR HA 445. AT 1200 CARGO SENT THE MANIFEST TO THE LOAD PLANNER, HOWEVER, NO SHIPMENT FOR HA 445 WAS INDICATED AS DG ON THE MANIFEST. THE LOAD PLANNER CALLED CARGO TO CONFIRM IF THERE WAS A DG SHIPMENT FOR HA 445 AND WAS TOLD THERE WAS NO DG FOR HA 445 WHICH CAUSED HIM TO ANNOTATE “NO DG” ON LOAD CLOSE OUT.   AFTER THE FLIGHT DEPARTED, THE LOAD MASTER TURNED IN HIS PAPERWORK TO THE LOAD PLANNER. THE LOAD PLANNER NOTICED A NOPIC THAT WAS NOT SIGNED BY THE LOAD MASTER, DID NOT ANNOTATE A CARGO LOCATION, AND DID NOT HAVE THE CAPTAIN’S SIGNATURE. THE NOPIC WAS PROPERLY PREPARED BY JFK ON JUNE 17, HOWEVER, THE LOAD MASTER FAILED TO COMPLETE THE FORM AND PROVIDED IT TO THE CAPTAIN FOR SIGNATURE. THE LOAD PLANNER CONTACTED DISPATCH AFTER VERIFYING WITH CARGO THAT DG WAS LOADED ABOARD HA 445. DISPATCH THEN CONTACTED THE PILOT IN-FLIGHT WITH THE DESCRIPTION AND LOADING INFORMATION. THE FLIGHT CONTINUED TO AKL WITHOUT A NOPIC ON-BOARD.  THIS INCIDENT HAS BEEN REPORTED TO FAA UNDER THE VOLUNTARY DISCLOSURE REPORTING (VDRP) PROCEDURE (ID#21048).
column169: THIS WAS THE CARGO MANIFESTER'S FIRST DAY ON THE JOB AND THOUGH THE PAPERWORK WAS PRESENT, BOTH AGENTS WHO TOOK THE CALLS FROM WEIGHT AND BALANCE SHOULD HAVE CAUGHT THE MISTAKE BY CHECKING THE SUPPORTING PAPERWORK BEHIND THE MANIFEST.   THE CARGO MAINIFESTER HAS BEEN COUNSELED TO CHECK HIS WORK AND, A PROPOSAL TO ADD AN ADDITIONAL MANIFESTER HAS BEEN MADE TO DISPERSE THE WORKLOAD OF 15 FLIGHTS TO MORE THAN ONE PERSON.   THE LOADMASTER WILL BE ENTERED INTO A RETRAINING PROGRAM FOR DANGEROUS GOODS HANDLING. A DOCUMENTED COPY OF COMPLETION WILL BE ENTERED INTO THE EMPLOYEE’S TRAINING LIFE.   IN ADDITION, A CHECKLIST WILL BE DEVELOPED FOR ALL LOADMASTER, AND WILL BE MANDATORY TO BE ATTACHED TO THE NOPIC DOCUMENTS. THE CHECKLIST WILL INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING:   - CONFIRMATION OF ONLOAD OF DG SHIPMENT AND DISPOSITION OF NOPIC COPIES.   - CONFIRMATION OF POSITION AND ONLOAD DURING FINAL CLOSEOUT MUST BE GIVEN TO LOAD PLANNER AS PART OF CHECKLIST ITEM.   LOADMASTER HAS ALSO BEEN ISSUED A DISCIPLINARY WRITTEN RECORD OF CORRECTIVE ACTION FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW PROPER PROCEDURES FOR HANDLING OF THE NOTICE TO PILOT OF COMMAND FORM. FAILURE OF PROPER SIGNATURES AND DISTRIBUTION IS DOCUMENTED IN THE WRITTEN WARNING.

column168: ON JUNE 21, 2017, AT APPROXIMATELY 15:30, ISOTAINER 63 (CAMU 2124412-4) ARRIVED AT MGC PURE CHEMICALS AMERICA (MPCA) AT OUR SECURITY/DELIVERY GATE. THE DRIVER INFORMED OUR SECURITY GUARD OF A SUSPECTED LEAK OF MATERIAL THE SECURITY GUARD OBSERVED MATERIAL DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER AND NOTIFIED MPCA PERSONNEL. THE CONTAINER WAS BROUGHT ON SITE AND STATIONED IN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THE CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC WAS COMPROMISED AND WAS THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. THE RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED AND THE CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC WAS COMPROMISED AND WAS THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. THE RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED AND THE CONTAINER WAS WEIGHED FULL AND THEN EMPTY. WE DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 21 GALLONS (220 POUNDS) OF MATERIAL HAD BEEN RELEASED. AT THE TIME, WE DID NOT KNOW THE AMOUNT SO MPCA PERSONNEL DECIDED TO NOTIFY THE NRC AS A PRECAUTION.
column169: MPCA REPLACED RUPTURE DISCS ON ALL STAINLESS STEEL (T14) CONTAINERS IN OUR FLEET.

column168: TEAM MEMBER WAS UNLOADING A TRUCK WITH A FORKLIFT. WHILE CARRYING A TOTE OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE, THE FORKLIFT DROVE OVER A LOW SPOT NEXT TO THE CONCRETE POND AND THE FORKLIFT STOPPED SUDDENLY. THE LIQUID IN THE TOTE RUSHED FORWARD AND CAUSED THE TOTE TO SLIP OFF THE FORKS AND ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD. THE TOTE BURST OPEN AND RESULTED IN APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND. THE TOTE WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACE UPRIGHT TO PREVENT MORE SPILLAGE. A DIKE OF GRAVEL AND DIRT WAS BUILT TO HELP CONTROL THE FLOW OF THE SPILL. THE SPILL RAN INTO A STORM DRAIN THAT WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE PLANT FOR USE THE SAME DAY.
column169: TO HELP PREVENT AN INCIDENT LIKE THIS IN THE FUTURE, SIGNAGE HAS BEEN PLACED IN THE UNLOADING AREA TO REMIND DELIVERY DRIVERS AND TEAM MEMBERS THAT TRUCKS MUST BACK UP ALL THE WAY TO THE CONCRETE PAD. THIS WILL ENSURE THAT THE FORKLIFT WILL ALWAYS BE ON LEVEL GROUND WHILE UNLOADING.

column168: ACCIDENT ON I-40 EB MM  132, IN ALBUQUERQUE NEW MEXICO AT 07:30AM ON 06/29/2017. NO OTHER PARTIES INVOLVED. DSR (DRIVER SALES REPRESENTATIVE) ROLLED REAR TRAILER. NO OTHER PARTIES INVOLVED. NO INJURIES. DAMAGE TO XPO REAR TRAILER SCRATCHES ON P/S. DSR WAS DRIVING ON I-40 EB NEAR MM 132. DSR STATED THAT HE DOZED OFF, CROSSING THE WHITE LINE, AND FELT HE WAS ON THE RUMBLE STRIP. DSR TURNED WHEN TRYING TO CORRECT THE TRACTOR FROM GOING INTO DITCH. THIS ROLLOVER OCCURRED ON STRAIGHT ROAD. THE TRACTOR AND UNITS ARE BLOCKING THE LEFT LANE. THE UNIT SLID 5 FT. THE SKID MARKS WERE ABOUT 5 FT. THE REAR BOX WEIGHT; 8000LBS. THE PINTLE HOOK TOP PART WAS TWISTED. LAW ENFORCEMENT IS ON THE SCENE; ALBUQUERQUE STATE POLICE. DSR WAS CITED FOR CARELESS DRIVING. THE SECOND TRAILER OVERTURNED ON IT RIGHT SIDE LAYING ACROSS BOTH LANES OF TRAFFIC ON I -40 EB. READINGS TAKEN FROM THE SECOND TRAILER. NO RELEASE OF MATERIAL. FREIGHT TRANSFERRED FROM SECOND TRAILER TO ANOTHER TRAILER AND TRANSPORTED TO SERVICE CENTER FOR FURTHER INSPECTIONS. ROAD REOPENED AT 16:25 ON 06/29/2017. NO OTHER DAMAGE NOTED DURING INSPECTION TO HM PACKAGING.
